    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The U.S. military posture and activity patterns suggest a heightened focus on maritime security and surveillance, particularly in the Western Pacific and Middle East. Carrier strike groups and amphibious ready groups are actively deployed, with forward-deployed assets in Japan and the Philippines maintaining persistent maritime presence to counter regional threats. The resumption of the U.S. naval blockade in the Strait of Hormuz signals a return to a more aggressive deterrence posture against Iran. In the Pacific, the presence of Marine Corps littoral combat teams in the Northern Philippines and ongoing RIMPAC 2026 exercises reflect a strategic focus on maritime domain awareness and rapid response capabilities. The U.S. Navy&#39;s fleet deployment numbers indicate a robust operational readiness, with forward-deployed destroyers and cruisers maintaining global reach. The U.S. Air Force&#39;s continued reliance on high-altitude tankers and command platforms supports global operations. Overall, the intelligence suggests a U.S. military actively engaged in deterrence, crisis response, and operational readiness across multiple theaters, with a clear emphasis on countering near-peer competitors and regional adversaries. The current operational tempo is expected to continue, with a focus on maintaining regional stability and securing critical maritime chokepoints. The U.S. military&#39;s ability to adapt to emerging threats and challenges will be crucial in maintaining its strategic advantage in the coming months.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
